The '''Party Crashers''' are a human militia dedicated to containing and eradicating the [[Sanguine Festivus]] virus and its victims. 
==<span style="position: relative; display: inline-block; margin-right: 2.5px; top: -2px;">[[File:Flashlight2.png|30px|link=]]</span> Description==
{{Blurimage|file=Party_Crasher_.png|caption=An illustration of typical Party Crasher attire.}}
With origins as far back as the early 1880s, the '''Party Crashers'''' incentive is to stomp out Partygoer presence wherever it may take root; whilst also providing ample aid and welfare to communities ravaged by the ongoing conflict. Although generally friendly to most communities, militants tend to have a merciless attitude towards the SFV virus, with each and every unit being equipped with ample ammunition and equipment to properly squash threats.

Members of the '''Party Crashers''' are easily identifiable by their dark-blue masks: which not only protect them from exposure to SFV but also serve as a means of identification from a distance, although this identification can be a disadvantage on occasion<ref>Examples include an incident during the Euphoric Wars when a large group of Jovials (presumed to be led by [[Caius Taggert]] himself) disguised as '''Party Crasher''' units and successfully infiltrated a settlement within [[Level 399]].</ref>. Along with this, units don grey hooded sweatshirts worn atop several layers of clothing, as well as padded cargo pants to limit exposure as much as possible. Certain crashers<ref>The group's term for a Party Crasher unit.</ref> opt to take their protective gear several steps further, reinforcing their attire with duct tape, additional fabrics, and scrap metal, with many including rudimentary metal helmets in their apparel. Regardless of these variations in attire, all crashers are identifiable by cloth bands tied around their left arm; with colors and stripes used to identify awards, ranks, and battalion.

A vast majority of '''Party Crasher''' units live in a nomadic lifestyle — with only a select few members persisting in small camps and settlements around populated levels as a form of chaos control. The member count of the '''Party Crashers''' is known to be extraordinarily high; as some estimates record their exact population to be somewhere in the tens of thousands. Gaining membership within the group is partly difficult, as a mandatory 15-day preventative quarantine is required, as well as extensive training on par with the United States Marines within: [[The Frontrooms]]. 

In terms of weaponry, the '''Party Crashers''' flaunt an extensive arsenal which has yet to be replicated by any group as of yet — with their main form of arms being cheap, yet effective firearms, with their undisclosed base of operations having ample resources to arm each member with variations of the Sten gun<ref>A cheap, mass-produced British submachine gun in [[The Frontrooms]].</ref>, as well as basic long-ranged firearms. Along with this, crasher units are also trained to weaponize objects, with many opting to utilize both [[Object 5|Greek Fire]] and [[Object 12|Liquid Pain]] due to their volatile properties. Experimental weapons, such as hardened liquid pain in the form of explosive blow-darts and volatile [[Object 15|Firesalt]] rounds have been demonstrated during the Euphoric wars with varying degrees of success.

===Organization===
The '''Party Crashers''' have an advanced hierarchy system; in which all initiate units have no rank at all and are incentivized to advance. In order to properly advance within the group hierarchy, one must display both good performance and merit; ranks within the group are similar to real-life military positions, such as colonel, lieutenant, and sergeant, among others. 

Most militias typically consist of around 100-200 crasher units, with a "Commandare"<ref>Archaic Latin word for 'commander'.</ref> commanding it, often being the highest-ranking unit within the militia. Squads of crasher units usually consist of around twenty, which are the defensive units stationed within outposts. 

Similar to [[The First]] within the [[M.E.G.]] hierarchy, the '''Party Crashers''' has a similar administrative figure known simply as "The Director". Whilst information regarding him is concealed, it is known that he is the person responsible for the offensives during the Euphoric War, as well as the reorganization of the group during the early 2000s. Units known as "Chevetaines"<ref>Archaic French word for 'captain'.</ref> function essentially as the group's form of Impresarios, being responsible for major war decisions and are in charge of the hierarchy. 

Whilst the '''Party Crashers''' tend to generally steer away from politics, the death of a Director results in a group election between the Chevetaines — with the highest voted individual ascending to a Director. Upon election, a new Chevetaine takes the empty spot left by the new leader. Each Director has a term of twenty years, albeit this can be extended upon re-election by the Chevetaine council. In the case of death, the Chevetaines assume a new leader into office.
==<span style="position: relative; display: inline-block; margin-right: 2.5px; top: -2px;">[[File:Flashlight2.png|30px|link=]]</span> History==
{{Blurimage|file=Partycrasher_Armor.png|caption=Artist illustration depicting two of many variations of Party Crasher apparel.}}
===Initial Beginnings===
The first recorded account of '''Party Crasher''' activity was in 1919, when the group was initially founded by a World War I veteran known as the "Anti-Jovial Militia", whose name has been lost to time. Reports indicate that he may have lived until the 1940s. As they did not have much activity the past fifty years, the '''Party Crashers''' as an organized group did not start to take form during the 1980s — when The Backrooms underwent a significant spike in the Jovial population. 

As populations increased, so did the amount of volunteers to help combat the infection, leading to the creation of battalions and small outposts. Since the crasher militias were primarily nomadic, they primarily focused on defense, deploying small groups of around ten to a number of bases as a preventative measure. 

===The Euphoric Wars===
The '''Party Crashers''' first gained significant publicity during the Euphoric Wars: starting in 2002 with an all-out Jovial attack on several settlements within [[Level 1]] and [[Level 4]]. The militias responded with one of the first demonstrations of Backrooms military might, with the 11th Eradication Battalion performing a sweeping attack on Jovial positions. Due to this, they managed to drive out a majority of Jovial forces within just a few weeks. Despite the initial Partygoer defeat, they did not show signs of backing down, retaliating with an all-out assault on the [[Level 399]] megacolony — with some witnesses stating the group may have been led by [[Caius Taggert]] himself. 

The attack on the Megacolony resulted in casualties in the thousands; as Jovials used both the weaponry of deceased crashers as well as effective military tactics in order to infect thousands of more individuals. Regardless, the amount of crashers within the level vastly outnumbered the Partygoer population, henceforth resulting in a decisive defeat. 

With the main Jovial force defeated, the '''Party Crashers''' decided to take the initiative — taking the fight to [[Level Fun]] itself to attempt a full eradication of the Sanguine Festivus virus. However, these efforts would initially be in vain, as numerous traps would be installed throughout the entire level in an attempt to apprehend and neutralize as many crasher units as possible; with large parts of the level being converted into rudimentary glue pits and spike traps.

The Euphoric Wars would eventually end in 2016, when [[Phenomenon 12|The Flicker]] put the group's operations on hold. 

===The Flicker===
With The Flicker ravaging the entire Backrooms, the '''Party Crashers''' were forced to temporary cease all operations amidst falling member counts and reduced morale. Many groups venturing out into the darkness would often not return, causing the group to cease their nomadic lifestyle. As a result of this, a major crasher site known as Cobalt Visage would be established, with a majority of units either flocking there or to the undisclosed level where the base of operations is located. 

Although the group saw no real troubles during The Flicker, Partygoer populations saw a significant spike as Jovial units would be sent into large groups to wreak havoc — including yet another attack on Level 399's megacolony with the help of [[Entity List|common entities]].

With the event predictably coming to an end around the early 2020s, the '''Party Crashers''' have thus resumed operation.

===Post-Flicker===
Today the '''Party Crashers''' are notably weaker in capability then they were prior to their efforts in the Euphoric Wars, but their mission to protect the Backrooms from SFV still continues with just as much resolve as they had beforehand, although with diminished numbers and munitions. Those who stop by most more well-populated colonies throughout the Backrooms are likely to find at least one recruitment officer for the militia, and trading outposts operated by the faction can be found on a handful of advantageous levels.

==<span style="position: relative; display: inline-block; margin-right: 2.5px; top: -2px;">[[File:Flashlight2.png|30px|link=]]</span> Relations==
Below is a list of groups that the '''Party Crashers''' have established relations with, or have units deployed in a foreign base there.

===[[M.E.G.|Major Explorer Group]]===
The M.E.G. is the '''Party Crashers'''' biggest partner; with there being crasher militias in close proximity to almost every major M.E.G. base as a result of their mutual defense pact. Trade is also a big portion of their relationship, with the two organizations exchanging arms and resources, with the crasher militias acting as a foreign military for the group.

===[[Republic of Aurielle]]===
Despite their warmongering, the '''Party Crashers''' and Aurielle have managed to maintain mutually positive relations with one another. From a public standpoint, they are not necessarily involved in affairs as often as other groups are, though Aurielle is partly responsible for several operations during the Euphoric Wars, as they had a minor role within the conflict.

===[[Architect Industries]]===
Architect Industries and the '''Party Crashers''' have been close partners since the former's founding in the 1970s, with the Architects giving technology in exchange for protection; including their groundbreaking Luvidium-Modified [[Object 29|Kalthoff Rifles]]].

===[[Backrooms Colonists]]===
The '''Party Crashers''' maintain a relatively neutral standing when it comes to the Backrooms Colonists — the two maintain relatively friendly relations, with both agreeing to respect one another's territory. As of now, crasher units are deployed in seven different bases belonging to the Backrooms Colonists.

===[[I.R.I.S.|Insurgent Rogueware and Infiltration Syndicate]]===
I.R.I.S. is the only group that the '''Party Crashers''' have a negative opinion of, with the hacking organization launching multiple malware attacks against crasher databases in recent years, aiming to retrieve vital information.

